  "prompt": "How can we prove that the square root of 2 is irrational?",
  "response": "To prove that the square root of 2 (\u221a2) is irrational, we'll use a classic method called **proof by contradiction**. This approach involves assuming the opposite of what you want to prove and then showing that this assumption leads to a logical inconsistency.\n\n### Step-by-Step Proof by Contradiction\n\n1. **Assume the Opposite:**  \n   Suppose that \u221a2 is **rational**. By definition, a rational number can be expressed as a fraction of two integers with no common factors (i.e., in lowest terms).  \n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{2} = \\frac{p}{q}\n   \\]\n   where \\( p \\) and \\( q \\) are integers with no common factors (i.e., their greatest common divisor is 1), and \\( q \\neq 0 \\).\n\n2. **Square Both Sides:**  \n   To eliminate the square root, square both sides of the equation:\n   \\[\n   2 = \\frac{p^2}{q^2}\n   \\]\n   Multiply both sides by \\( q^2 \\) to simplify:\n   \\[\n   2q^2 = p^2\n   \\]\n\n3. **Implications for \\( p \\):**  \n   The equation \\( 2q^2 = p^2 \\) implies that \\( p^2 \\) is even because it is equal to twice another integer (\\( q^2 \\) is an integer since \\( q \\) is an integer).  \n   If \\( p^2 \\) is even, then \\( p \\) itself must also be even (since the square of an odd number is odd).\n\n4. **Express \\( p \\) as Even:**  \n   Since \\( p \\) is even, there exists an integer \\( k \\) such that:\n   \\[\n   p = 2k\n   \\]\n   \n5. **Substitute \\( p = 2k \\) Back Into the Equation:**  \n   Plugging \\( p = 2k \\) into \\( 2q^2 = p^2 \\):\n   \\[\n   2q^2 = (2k)^2 \\\\\n   2q^2 = 4k^2 \\\\\n   q^2 = 2k^2\n   \\]\n   \n6. **Implications for \\( q \\):**  \n   The equation \\( q^2 = 2k^2 \\) implies that \\( q^2 \\) is even, and therefore \\( q \\) must also be even.\n\n7. **Contradiction Arises:**  \n   If both \\( p \\) and \\( q \\) are even, then they have a common factor of 2. This contradicts our initial assumption that \\( p \\) and \\( q \\) have no common factors (i.e., the fraction \\( \\frac{p}{q} \\) was in lowest terms).\n\n8. **Conclusion:**  \n   Since our assumption that \u221a2 is rational leads to a contradiction, the original assumption must be false. Therefore, **\u221a2 is irrational**.\n\n### Summary\n\nBy assuming that \u221a2 can be expressed as a ratio of two integers with no common factors and showing that this leads to both integers being even (hence having a common factor of 2), we've arrived at a logical contradiction. This contradiction implies that our initial assumption is false, and thus, \u221a2 cannot be expressed as a ratio of two integers\u2014it is **irrational**.",
